<doc id="355140" wikidata="Q1630568" url="?curid=355140" title="Monad (category theory)">
<text>In category theory, a branch of mathematics, a monad is a triple formula_1 consisting of a functor &quot;T&quot; from a category to itself and two natural transformations formula_2 that satisfy the conditions like associativity. For example, if formula_3 are functors adjoint to each other, then formula_4 together with formula_2 determined by the adjoint relation is a monad.

In concise terms, a monad is a monoid in the category of endofunctors of some fixed category (an endofunctor is a functor mapping a category to itself). According to John Baez, a monad can be considered at least in two ways: 
# A monad as a generalized monoid; this is clear since a monad is a monoid in a certain category,
# A monad as a tool for studying algebraic gadgets; for example, a group can be described by a certain monad.

Monads are used in the theory of pairs of adjoint functors, and they generalize closure operators on partially ordered sets to arbitrary categories. Monads are also useful in the theory of datatypes, the denotational semantics of imperative programming languages, and in functional programming languages, allowing languages without mutable state to do things such as simulate for-loops; see Monad (functional programming).

A monad is also called, especially in old literature, a triple, triad, standard construction and fundamental construction.

== Introduction and definition ==

A monad is a certain type of endofunctor. For example, if formula_6 and formula_7 are a pair of adjoint functors, with formula_6 left adjoint to formula_7, then the composition formula_10 is a monad. If formula_6 and formula_7 are inverse to each other, the corresponding monad is the identity functor. In general, adjunctions are not equivalences—they relate categories of different natures. The monad theory matters as part of the effort to capture what it is that adjunctions &#x27;preserve&#x27;. The other half of the theory, of what can be learned likewise from consideration of formula_13, is discussed under the dual theory of &quot;comonads&quot;.

===Formal definition===

Throughout this article, formula_14 denotes a category. A &quot;monad&quot; on formula_14 consists of an endofunctor formula_16 together with two natural transformations: formula_17 (where formula_18 denotes the identity functor on formula_14) and formula_20 (where formula_21 is the functor formula_22 from formula_14 to formula_14). These are required to fulfill the following conditions (sometimes called coherence conditions):

* formula_25 (as natural transformations formula_26); here formula_27 and formula_28 are formed by &quot;horizontal composition&quot;.
* formula_29 (as natural transformations formula_30; here formula_31 denotes the identity transformation from formula_32 to formula_32).

We can rewrite these conditions using the following commutative diagrams:
See the article on natural transformations for the explanation of the notations formula_27 and formula_28, or see below the commutative diagrams not using these notions:

The first axiom is akin to the associativity in monoids if we think of formula_36 as the monoid&#x27;s binary operation, and the second axiom is akin to the existence of an identity element (which we think of as given by formula_37). Indeed, a monad on formula_14 can alternatively be defined as a monoid in the category formula_39 whose objects are the endofunctors of formula_14 and whose morphisms are the natural transformations between them, with the monoidal structure induced by the composition of endofunctors.

===The power set monad===

The &quot;power set monad&quot; is a monad formula_41 on the category formula_42: For a set formula_43 let formula_44 be the power set of formula_43 and for a function formula_46 let formula_47 be the function between the power sets induced by taking direct images under formula_48. For every set formula_43, we have a map formula_50, which assigns to every formula_51 the singleton formula_52. The function

:formula_53

takes a set of sets to its union. These data describe a monad.

===Remarks===
The axioms of a monad are formally similar to the monoid axioms. In fact, monads are special cases of monoids, namely they are precisely the monoids among endofunctors formula_54, which is equipped with the multiplication given by composition of endofunctors.

Composition of monads is not, in general, a monad. For example, the double power set functor formula_55 does not admit any monad structure.

=== Comonads ===
The categorical dual definition is a formal definition of a &quot;comonad&quot; (or &quot;cotriple&quot;); this can be said quickly in the terms that a comonad for a category formula_14 is a monad for the opposite category formula_57. It is therefore a functor formula_58 from formula_14 to itself, with a set of axioms for &quot;counit&quot; and &quot;comultiplication&quot; that come from reversing the arrows everywhere in the definition just given.

Monads are to monoids as comonads are to &quot;comonoids&quot;. Every set is a comonoid in a unique way, so comonoids are less familiar in abstract algebra than monoids; however, comonoids in the category of vector spaces with its usual tensor product are important and widely studied under the name of coalgebras.

===Terminological history===
The notion of monad was invented by Roger Godement in 1958 under the name &quot;standard construction&quot;. Monad has been called &quot;dual standard construction&quot;, &quot;triple&quot;, &quot;monoid&quot; and &quot;triad&quot;. The term &quot;monad&quot; is used at latest 1967, by Jean Bénabou.

==Examples==

===Identity===

The identity functor on a category formula_14 is a monad. Its multiplication and unit are the identity function on the objects of formula_14.

===Monads arising from adjunctions===

Any adjunction

:formula_62

gives rise to a monad on &quot;C&quot;. This very widespread construction works as follows: the endofunctor is the composite

:formula_63

This endofunctor is quickly seen to be a monad, where the unit map stems from the unit map formula_64 of the adjunction, and the multiplication map is constructed using the counit map of the adjunction:

:formula_65
In fact, any monad can be found as an explicit adjunction of functors using the Eilenberg–Moore category formula_66 (the category of formula_32-algebras).

====Double dualization====
The &quot;double dualization monad&quot;, for a fixed field &quot;k&quot; arises from the adjunction

:formula_68

where both functors are given by sending a vector space &quot;V&quot; to its dual vector space formula_69. The associated monad sends a vector space &quot;V&quot; to its double dual formula_70. This monad is discussed, in much greater generality, by .

====Closure operators on partially ordered sets====
For categories arising from partially ordered sets formula_71 (with a single morphism from formula_72 to formula_73 if and only if formula_74), then the formalism becomes much simpler: adjoint pairs are Galois connections and monads are closure operators.

====Free-forgetful adjunctions====
For example, let formula_7 be the forgetful functor from the category Grp of groups to the category Set of sets, and let formula_6 be the free group functor from the category of sets to the category of groups. Then formula_6 is left adjoint of formula_7. In this case, the associated monad formula_4 takes a set formula_80 and returns the underlying set of the free group formula_81.
The unit map of this monad is given by the maps
:formula_82
including any set formula_80 into the set formula_81 in the natural way, as strings of length 1. Further, the multiplication of this monad is the map
:formula_85
made out of a natural concatenation or &#x27;flattening&#x27; of &#x27;strings of strings&#x27;. This amounts to two natural transformations.
The preceding example about free groups can be generalized to any type of algebra in the sense of a variety of algebras in universal algebra. Thus, every such type of algebra gives rise to a monad on the category of sets. Importantly, the algebra type can be recovered from the monad (as the category of Eilenberg–Moore algebras), so monads can also be seen as generalizing varieties of universal algebras.

Another monad arising from an adjunction is when formula_32 is the endofunctor on the category of vector spaces which maps a vector space formula_87 to its tensor algebra formula_88, and which maps linear maps to their tensor product. We then have a natural transformation corresponding to the embedding of formula_87 into its tensor algebra, and a natural transformation corresponding to the map from formula_90 to formula_88 obtained by simply expanding all tensor products.

===Codensity monads===

Under mild conditions, functors not admitting a left adjoint also give rise to a monad, the so-called codensity monad. For example, the inclusion

:formula_92

does not admit a left adjoint. Its codensity monad is the monad on sets sending any set &quot;X&quot; to the set of ultrafilters on &quot;X&quot;. This and similar examples are discussed in .

===Monads used in denotational semantics===

The following monads over the category of sets are used in denotational semantics of imperative programming languages, and analogous constructions are used in functional programming.

====The maybe monad====

The endofunctor of the maybe or partiality monad adds a disjoint point:

:formula_93
:formula_94

The unit is given by the inclusion of a set formula_80 into formula_96:

:formula_97
:formula_98

The multiplication maps elements of formula_80 to themselves, and the two disjoint points in formula_100 to the one in formula_101.

In both functional programming and denotational semantics, the maybe monad models partial computations, that is, computations that may fail.

====The state monad====

Given a set formula_102, the endofunctor of the state monad maps each set formula_80 to the set of functions formula_104. The component of the unit at formula_80 maps each element formula_106 to the function

:formula_107
:formula_108

The multiplication maps the function formula_109 to the function

:formula_110
:formula_111

In functional programming and denotational semantics, the state monad models stateful computations.

====The environment monad====

Given a set formula_112, the endofunctor of the reader or environment monad maps each set formula_80 to the set of functions formula_114. Thus, the endofunctor of this monad is exactly the hom functor formula_115. The component of the unit at formula_80 maps each element formula_106 to the constant function formula_118.

In functional programming and denotational semantics, the environment monad models computations with access to some read-only data.

====The list and set monads====

The list or nondeterminism monad maps a set &quot;X&quot; to the set of finite sequences (i.e., lists) with elements from &quot;X&quot;. The unit maps an element &quot;x&quot; in &quot;X&quot; to the singleton list [x]. The multiplication concatenates a list of lists into a single list.

In functional programming, the list monad is used to model nondeterministic computations. The covariant powerset monad is also known as the set monad, and is also used to model nondeterministic computation.

== Algebras for a monad ==
Given a monad formula_119 on a category formula_14, it is natural to consider &quot;formula_32-algebras&quot;, i.e., objects of formula_14 acted upon by formula_32 in a way which is compatible with the unit and multiplication of the monad. More formally, a formula_32-algebra formula_125 is an object formula_72 of formula_14 together with an arrow formula_128 of formula_14 called the &quot;structure map&quot; of the algebra such that the diagrams

commute.

A morphism formula_130 of formula_32-algebras is an arrow formula_132 of formula_14 such that the diagram commutes. formula_32-algebras form a category called the &quot;Eilenberg–Moore category&quot; and denoted by formula_66.

=== Examples ===

==== Algebras over the free group monad ====
For example, for the free group monad discussed above, a formula_32-algebra is a set formula_80 together with a map from the free group generated by formula_80 towards formula_80 subject to associativity and unitality conditions. Such a structure is equivalent to saying that formula_80 is a group itself.

==== Algebras over the distribution monad ====
Another example is the distribution monad formula_141 on the category of sets. It is defined by sending a set formula_80 to the set of functions formula_143 with finite support and such that their sum is equal to formula_144. In set-builder notation, this is the setformula_145By inspection of the definitions, it can be shown that algebras over the distribution monad are equivalent to convex sets, i.e., sets equipped with operations formula_146 for formula_147 subject to axioms resembling the behavior of convex linear combinations formula_148 in Euclidean space.

==== Algebras over the symmetric monad ====
Another useful example of a monad is the symmetric algebra functor on the category of formula_149-modules for a commutative ring formula_149.formula_151sending an formula_149-module formula_153 to the direct sum of symmetric tensor powersformula_154where formula_155. For example, formula_156 where the formula_149-algebra on the right is considered as a module. Then, an algebra over this monad are commutative formula_149-algebras. There are also algebras over the monads for the alternating tensors formula_159 and total tensor functors formula_160 giving anti-symmetric formula_149-algebras, and free formula_149-algebras, soformula_163where the first ring is the free anti-symmetric algebra over formula_149 in formula_165-generators and the second ring is the free algebra over formula_149 in formula_165-generators.

==== Commutative algebras in E-infinity ring spectra ====
There is an analogous construction for commutative formula_168-algebraspg 113 which gives commutative formula_43-algebras for a commutative formula_168-algebra formula_43. If formula_172 is the category of formula_43-modules, then the functor formula_174 is the monad given byformula_175whereformula_176 formula_177-times. Then there is an associated category formula_178 of commutative formula_43-algebras from the category of algebras over this monad.

== Monads and adjunctions ==
As was mentioned above, any adjunction gives rise to a monad. Conversely, every monad arises from some adjunction, namely the free–forgetful adjunction

:formula_180

whose left adjoint sends an object &quot;X&quot; to the free &quot;T&quot;-algebra &quot;T&quot;(&quot;X&quot;). However, there are usually several distinct adjunctions giving rise to a monad: let formula_181 be the category whose objects are the adjunctions formula_182 such that formula_183 and whose arrows are the morphisms of adjunctions that are the identity on formula_14. Then the above free–forgetful adjunction involving the Eilenberg–Moore category formula_66 is a terminal object in formula_181. An initial object is the Kleisli category, which is by definition the full subcategory of formula_66 consisting only of free &quot;T&quot;-algebras, i.e., &quot;T&quot;-algebras of the form formula_188 for some object &quot;x&quot; of &quot;C&quot;.

===Monadic adjunctions===

Given any adjunction formula_189 with associated monad &quot;T&quot;, the functor &quot;G&quot; can be factored as

:formula_190

i.e., &quot;G&quot;(&quot;Y&quot;) can be naturally endowed with a &quot;T&quot;-algebra structure for any &quot;Y&quot; in &quot;D&quot;. The adjunction is called a monadic adjunction if the first functor formula_191 yields an equivalence of categories between &quot;D&quot; and the Eilenberg–Moore category formula_66. By extension, a functor formula_193 is said to be monadic if it has a left adjoint formula_6 forming a monadic adjunction. For example, the free–forgetful adjunction between groups and sets is monadic, since algebras over the associated monad are groups, as was mentioned above. In general, knowing that an adjunction is monadic allows one to reconstruct objects in &quot;D&quot; out of objects in &quot;C&quot; and the &quot;T&quot;-action.

===Beck&#x27;s monadicity theorem===

&quot;Beck&#x27;s monadicity theorem&quot; gives a necessary and sufficient condition for an adjunction to be monadic. A simplified version of this theorem states that &quot;G&quot; is monadic if it is conservative (or &quot;G&quot; reflects isomorphisms, i.e., a morphism in &quot;D&quot; is an isomorphism if and only if its image under &quot;G&quot; is an isomorphism in &quot;C&quot;) and &quot;C&quot; has and &quot;G&quot; preserves coequalizers.

For example, the forgetful functor from the category of compact Hausdorff spaces to sets is monadic. However the forgetful functor from all topological spaces to sets is not conservative since there are continuous bijective maps (between non-compact or non-Hausdorff spaces) that fail to be homeomorphisms. Thus, this forgetful functor is not monadic.
The dual version of Beck&#x27;s theorem, characterizing comonadic adjunctions, is relevant in different fields such as topos theory and topics in algebraic geometry related to descent. A first example of a comonadic adjunction is the adjunction

:formula_195

for a ring homomorphism formula_196 between commutative rings. This adjunction is comonadic, by Beck&#x27;s theorem, if and only if &quot;B&quot; is faithfully flat as an &quot;A&quot;-module. It thus allows to descend &quot;B&quot;-modules, equipped with a descent datum (i.e., an action of the comonad given by the adjunction) to &quot;A&quot;-modules. The resulting theory of faithfully flat descent is widely applied in algebraic geometry.

== Uses ==

Monads are used in functional programming to express types of sequential computation (sometimes with side-effects). See monads in functional programming, and the more mathematically oriented Wikibook module .

Monads are used in the denotational semantics of impure functional and imperative programming languages.

In categorical logic, an analogy has been drawn between the monad-comonad theory, and modal logic via closure operators, interior algebras, and their relation to models of S4 and intuitionistic logics.

==Generalization==
It is possible to define monads in a 2-category formula_14. Monads described above are monads for formula_198.

